# GameNative — Wine / Proton Version Management

## Overview — how it works and why it's the right approach

**How GameHub does it:** It does not bundle any Wine or Proton binaries in the APK (that would make the APK gigabytes). Instead it hits GitHub's public releases API to get a list of every available version, shows them all in a list, and downloads whichever ones the user wants on demand. The APK only contains the version list logic, not the actual runtimes.

**Our implementation** pulls from four sources — **Proton-GE** (GloriousEggroll, best compatibility), **Kron4ek Wine** builds (lightweight, good for older DX9/DX11 games), **Valve Proton** (official), and **Wine-GE** (for non-Steam launchers). Each has its own GitHub repo and the fetcher knows exactly which asset file to look for in each release.

The **version list screen** shows the latest 5 versions by default with a "Show older versions" button to expand to all 20. Each row shows the version name, date, size, and badges — **LATEST** (teal), **RECOMMENDED** (set by the hardware recommender), **ACTIVE** (currently selected for this specific game). Not-installed versions get a **Download** button. Installed-but-not-active versions get **Use** and **Remove**. The active version just shows a checkmark — you can't accidentally remove it.

The **Compatibility Layer picker** in Game Settings is a quick bottom sheet showing only already-installed versions (fast, no network needed). At the bottom there's a **"Download more versions →"** button that takes you to the full Component screen to fetch and install additional ones. Same flow as GameHub — quick picker for switching, separate screen for downloading.

**Key detail:** **ACTIVE is per-game** and stored in its own Room table. Game A can use Proton-GE 9-20 while Game B uses Proton-GE 9-27 simultaneously. That's what the **active_runtimes** table with `(appId, source)` as the primary key handles.

---

## How GameHub does it (and how we replicate it) — detail

GameHub fetches a list of ALL available releases from GitHub's public
releases API for each runtime source. It does NOT bundle any versions —
it only bundles a version list and downloads on demand. When the app
first opens the Component screen it hits the GitHub API, gets the full
release list, and shows every version. The latest is marked recommended.
Every other version is available to download. Once downloaded, any version
can be set as active for a specific game.

Our implementation does the same thing with four runtime sources:

| Source           | GitHub repo                          | What it provides              |
|------------------|--------------------------------------|-------------------------------|
| Proton-GE        | GloriousEggroll/proton-ge-custom     | Best compatibility, community |
| Kron4ek Wine     | Kron4ek/Wine-Builds                  | Lightweight Wine builds       |
| Valve Proton     | ValveSoftware/Proton                 | Official Valve releases       |
| Wine-GE          | GloriousEggroll/wine-ge-custom       | Wine fork for non-Steam games |

